              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Is Canva a nice-to-have tool?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-nov-21-1.jpg" alt="Is Canva a nice-to-have tool?" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In 2007, as a student at the University of Western Australia, Melanie Perkins noticed that students struggled with the complicated and expensive design software used to create school yearbooks. While others saw the issue as a minor inconvenience, Melanie saw an opportunity to simplify a process that should have been easy. She launched Fusion Books, a website where students could create and print their yearbooks using templates and drag-and-drop tools. The idea was a hit in Australia, but Melanie didn’t stop there.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">As Fusion Books grew, Melanie realized that the frustration with design tools was not unique to yearbook creation—everyone from businesses to bloggers faced the same problem. But convincing others of her vision wasn’t easy. In fact, Melanie was rejected by 100 potential investors when she first pitched the idea for Canva. Many dismissed her concept as “nice-to-have” rather than revolutionary. One investor even told her that her idea of a design tool for “non-designers” wouldn’t work. Undeterred, Melanie persevered and finally found the support she needed. She secured a $3 million investment from venture capitalist Bill Tai, who believed in her vision.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">What truly made Canva a game-changer was its focus on collaboration. While many design tools were just for individual use, Canva enabled real-time collaboration, allowing teams to work together on designs no matter where they were.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In just a few years, Canva exploded in popularity. The platform became a go-to tool for individuals, businesses, and even large corporations. By 2019, just six years after launch, Canva reached $1 billion in valuation, making Melanie Perkins one of the youngest female CEOs to achieve such a milestone. </p>
          </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
